2026-06-17 14:56:48 | DEBUG    | openai._base_client  | Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/deployments/text-embedding-3-small/embeddings', 'headers': {'api-key': '<redacted>'}, 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-b9fca48c-f4c9-4356-850a-b4a7b56617d7', 'post_parser': <function Embeddings.create.<locals>.parser at 0x00000285D37D1BC0>, 'security': {'bearer_auth': True}, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'input': ['1 1. ELECTRIC CURRENT “The flow of charge in a definite direction constitutes the electric current and the time rate of flow of charge through any cross-section of a conductor is the measure of current”. i.e., net charge flown q dq Electric current, I= time taken t dt \x01 \x01 1', '. Though the “electric current represents the direction of flow of positive charge”. 2. Yet it is treated as a scalar quantity. 3. Current follows, the laws of scalar addition and not the laws of vector addition. 4', '. 4. Because the angle between the wires carrying currents does not affect the total current in the circuit. 2. CURRENT CARRIERS (a) Current carriers in solid conductors : 1', '. In solid conductors like metals, the valence electrons of the atoms do not remain attached to individual atoms but are free to move throughout the volume of the conductor. 2', '. 2. Under the effect of an external electric field, the valence electrons move in a definite direction causing electric current in the conductors. 3. Thus, valence electrons are the current carriers in solid conductors. (b) Current carriers in liquids : 1. In an electrolyte like CuSO4, NaCl etc', '. In an electrolyte like CuSO4, NaCl etc., there are positively and negatively charged ions (like 4 Cu , SO , Na , Cl \x02\x02 \x03\x03 \x02 \x03 ). 2. These are forced to move in definite directions under the effect of an external electric field, causing electric current. 3', '. 3. Thus, in liquids, the current carriers are positively and negatively charged ions. (c) Current carriers in gases : 1. Ordinarily, the gases are insulators of electricity. 2. They can be ionized by applying a high potential difference at low pressure 3', '. Thus, positive ions and electrons are the current carriers in gases. 3.  DRIFT VELOCITY “If 1 2 3 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 n u , u , u , ...u  are random thermal velocities of n free electrons in the metal conductor, then the average thermal velocity of electrons is 1 3 0 \x02 \x02 \x02 \x02 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 n u u u ..', '... u n As a result, there will be no net flow of electrons of charge in one particular direction in a metal conductor, hence no current”', '. “Drift velocity is defined as the average velocity with which the free electrons get drifted towards the positive end of the conductor under the influence of an external electric field applied”. 1. The drift velocity of electons is of the order of 10 –4 ms –1. 2', '. 2. If V is the potential difference applied across the ends of the conductor of length l, the magnitude of electric field set up is Potential difference V E length \x01 \x01 \x02 3. Each free electrons in the conductor experience a force, F eE. \x01 \x03 \x01 \x01 4. The acceleration of each electron is eE a m \x01 \x01 \x01', '. 5. At any instant of time, the velocity acquired by electron having thermal velocity 1u\x01  will be 1 1 1 v u a \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 where 1\x04  is the time elapsed since it has suffered its last collision with ion/atom of the conductor. CURRENT ELECTRICITY JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www', '.esaral.com Rev. Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2', '2 6. Similarly, the velocities acquired by other electrons in the conductor will be 2 2 2 v u a , \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 3 3 3 v u a , \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 ....., n n n v u a . \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 7', '....., n n n v u a . \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 7. The average velocity of all the free electrons in the conductor under the effect of external electric field is the drift velocity d v\x01  of the free electrons. Thus, 2 n d v v ... v v n \x02 \x02 \x02 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 1 2 2 n n u a u a ..', '... v v n \x02 \x02 \x02 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 1 2 2 n n u a u a ... u a n \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 2 n 1 2 n ... u u ... u a n n \x04 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x02 \x05 \x06 \x01 \x02 \x07 \x08 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 0 a a \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x04 \x01 \x01 where, 2 n ..', '... n \x04 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x04 \x01 = average time that has elapsed since each electron suffered its last collision with the ion/ atom of conductor and is called average relaxation time. 8. Its value is the order of 10 –14 second. 9', '. 8. Its value is the order of 10 –14 second. 9. Putting the value of a\x01  in the above relation, we have d eE v m \x03 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 Average drift speed, d eE v m \x01 \x04 The negative sign show that d v\x01  is opposite to the direction of E \x01 . 3', '. 3.1 Relaxation time (\x04 \x04 \x04 \x04 ) The time interval between two successive collisions of electrons with the positive ions in the metallic lattice is defined as relaxation time rms mean free path r.m.s. velocity of electrons v \x04 \x01 \x01 . With rise in temperature vrms increases consequently \x04 decreases. 3', '. 3.2   Mobility Drift velocity per unit electric field is called mobility of electron i.e. d v E \x01 It’s unit is 2 m volt sec \x03 \x01 If cross-section is constant, I \x0e J i.e. for a given cross-sectional area, greater the current density, larger will be current', '. \x01 The drift velocity of electrons is small because of the frequent collisions suffered by electrons. \x01 The small value of drift velocity produces a large amount of electric current, due to the presence of extremely large number of free electrons in a conductor', '. The propagation of current is almost at the speed of light and involves electromagnetic process. It is due to this reason that the electric bulb glows i