s a resistance R then the work done by the electric field on charge q to flow through the circuit in time t will be W = qV = Vit = i2R 2 V t Joule R \x01', '. This work appears as thermal energy in the resistor. Heat produced by the resistance R is 2 2 W Vit i Rt V t H Cal. J 4 2 4 2 4 2R \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 This relation is called joules heating', '. Some important relations for solving objective questions are as follow : JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev. Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2', '18 Condition Graph If R and t are constant 2 H i \x0e and 2 H V \x0e If i and t are constant (series grouping) H R \x0e If V and t are constant (Parallel grouping) 1 H R \x0e If V, i and R constant H t \x0e 13', '.1   Electric Power The rate at which electrical energy is dissipated into other forms of energy is called electrical power i.e. 2 2 W V P = = Vi = i R = t R (1) Units : It’s S.I. unit is Joule/sec or Watt Bigger S.I', '.I. unit is Joule/sec or Watt Bigger S.I. units are KW, MW and HP, remember 1 HP = 746 Watt (2) Rated values : On electrical appliances (Bulbs, Heater … etc.) Wattage, voltage, ……. etc. are printed called rated values e.g', '. etc. are printed called rated values e.g. If suppose we have a bulb of 40 W, 220 V then rated power (PR) = 40 W while rated voltage (VR) = 220 V', '. It means that on operating the bulb at 220 volt, the power dissipated will be 40 W or in other words 40 J of electrical energy will be converted into heat and light per second', '. (3) Resistance of electrical appliance : If variation of resistance with temperature is neglected then resistance of any electrical appliance can be calculated by rated power and rated voltage i.e. by using 2 R R V R = P e.g', '.e. by using 2 R R V R = P e.g. Resistance of 100W, 220 volt bulb is 220 220 R 484 100 \x18 \x01 \x01 \x19 (4) Power consumed (illumination) : An electrical appliance (Bulb, heater, …. etc.) consume rated power (PR) only if applied voltage (VA) is equal to rated voltage (VR) i.e. If VA = VR  so Pconsumed = PR', '.e. If VA = VR  so Pconsumed = PR. If VA < VR then 2 A consumed V P R \x01 also we have 2 R R V R P \x01 so 2 A consumed R 2 R V P (Brightness) .P V \x05 \x06 \x01 \x07 \x08 consumed P (Brightness) \x0e e.g', '.g. If 100 W, 220 V bulb operates on 110 volt supply then 2 consumed 110 P 100 25W 220 \x05 \x06 \x01 \x18 \x01 \x07 \x08 If VA < VR then % drop in output power R consumed R (P P ) 100 P \x03 \x01 \x18 For the series combination of bulbs, current through them will be same so they will consume power in the ratio of resistance i.e', '.e., P \x0e R {By P = i2R) while if they are connected in parallel i.e. V is constant so power consumed by them is in the reverse ratio of their resistance i.e', '.e. 1 P R \x0e (5) Thickness of filament of bulb : We know that resistance of filament of bulb is given by 2 R R V R , P \x01 also R , A \x01 \x17 l hence we can say that R Thickness 1 A P R \x0e \x0e i.e. If rated power of a bulb is more, thickness of it’s filament is also more and it’s resistance will be less', '. JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev. Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2', '19 If applied voltage is constant then (consumed) 1 P R \x01 (By 2 A V P R \x02 )', '. Hence if different bulbs (electrical appliance) operated at same voltage supply then consumed R 1 P P thickness R \x01 \x01 \x01 Different bulbs \x03 Resistance R25 > R100 > R1000 \x03 Thickness of filament t1000– > t100 > t40 \x03 Brightness B1000 > B100 > B25 (6) Long distance power transmission : When power is', 'Long distance power transmission : When power is transmitted through a power line of resistance R, power- loss will be R i2 Now if the power P is transmitted at voltage V P = Vi  i', '.e. i = (P/V)  So, 2 2 P Power loss R V \x02 \x04 Now as for a given power and line, P and R are constant so Power loss \x01 (1/V2) So if power is transmitted at high voltage, power loss will be small and vice-versa. e.g.,