ircuit when the electrical power in the circuit is 1 KWH thus 1 KWH = 1000 W \x04 3600 sec = 3.6 \x04 106 J. JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev\n\n[Source: electricity.pdf | Page: 18 | Chunk: 207]\n.1   Electric Power The rate at which electrical energy is dissipated into other forms of energy is called electrical power i.e. 2 2 W V P = = Vi = i R = t R (1) Units : It’s S.I. unit is Joule/sec or Watt Bigger S.I\n\n[Source: electricity.pdf | Page: 19 | Chunk: 228]\n.3 Electricity Consumption (1) The price of electricity consumed is calculated on the basis of electrical energy and not on the basis of electrical power. (2) The unit Joule for energy is very small hence a big practical unit is considered known as kilowatt hour (KWH) or board of trade unit (B.T.U\n\n[Source: electricity.pdf | Page: 10 | Chunk: 118]\n. It’s S.I. unit is ampere (A) and C.G.S. unit is emu and is called biot (Bi), or ab ampere. 1A = (1/10) Bi (ab amp.) (2) Ampere of current means the flow of 6.25 \x18 1018 electrons/sec through any cross–section of the conductor\n\n[Source: electricity.pdf | Page: 20 | Chunk: 231]\n20 (4) Important formulae to calculate the no. of consumed units is Total watt Total hours n 1000 \x18 \x01 13.4  Combination of Bulbs (or Electrical Appliances) Bulbs (Heater etc.) Bulbs (Heater etc.) are in series are in parallel (1)Total power consumed (1) Total power consumed total 1 2 1 1 1 ...\n\n[Source: electricity.pdf | Page: 19 | Chunk: 227]\n. 1 kWh = 1000 Wh = (1000 W) × (60 × 60 s) = 3.6 × 10 6 J. Note that the number of units of electricity consumed = No. of kWh = watt hour 1000 \x04 2 2 Electric energy VI t I Rt V t / R \x02 \x02 \x02 13\n\n[Source: electricity.pdf | Page: 19 | Chunk: 226]\nor UNIT of Electricity, in brief, where 1 kWh = 1 kilo watt × 1 hour = 1000 watt × 1 hour Thus 1 kilo watt hour is the total electric energy consumed when an electrical appliance of power 1 kilo-watt works for one hours\n\n[Source: electricity.pdf | P